Cindy Sheehan, a grieving mother who lost her son in Iraq, demands answers from President Bush.
She questions the justification for the war and the loss of lives.
She seeks a meeting with Bush to express her pain and frustration.
She has become a symbol of the anti-war movement, drawing support and attention nationwide.
Despite facing resistance, she remains steadfast in her protest near Bush's ranch.
The White House acknowledges her grief but emphasizes the importance of completing the mission in Iraq for national security.
Sheehan's determination and courage highlight the ongoing debate over the war's impact and the sacrifices made.
